    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Beat the Cheaters</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ethan Taub letter asks why University of Virginia professor needed computer to tell him he had received 60 identical term papers; suggests he might have caught on somewhat earlier in his reading of them (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''U. of Virginia Hit by Scandal Over Cheating'' (front page, May 10):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''U. of Virginia Hit by Scandal Over Cheating'' (front page, May 10):</p>
        <p>As a former college student, I have as little sympathy for cheaters as anyone else. Yet something else troubles me about the revelations from the University of Virginia. It seems odd that a professor needs a computer to tell him that he has received 60 identical term papers in five semesters. Why didn't he catch on after, say, the 28th reading?</p>
        <p>ETHAN TAUB  Zurich, May 10, 2001</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
